4n8.title: Why is the decimal expansion of log2(3) infinite?
4n8.text: It takes more than one but less than two [binary_digit binary digits] to encode a [n_digit 3-digit], so $1 < \log_2(3) < 2.$ ([427 Wait, what?]). It takes more than 15 but less than 16 binary digits to encode ten 3-digits, so $15 < 10 \cdot \log_2(3) < 16,$ and $1.5 < \log_2(3) < 1.6.$ It takes more than 158 but less than 159 binary digits to encode a hundred 3-digits, so $1.58 < \log_2(3) < 1.59.$ And so on. Because no power of 3 is ever equal to any power of 2, $10^n \cdot \log_2(3)$ will never quite be a whole number, no matter how large $n$ is. That is, $\log_2(3)$ has no finite decimal expansion because $2$ and $3$ are [-relatively_prime].
